The modern refugee system was established after World War II by these people.
Its original intention was to ensure that when a country collapses or, worse, when the government is hostile to its people, these people have somewhere to seek refuge, where they can live safely and with dignity until they can return home.
This is exactly the situation we see today in Syria.
Through the international conference signed by 147 governments in 1951, the Convention relating to the Status of Refugees, and an international organization, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), committing to allow people from other countries to enter their territory to escape conflict and persecution.
But now, this system is collapsing.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek asylum.
In reality, our immigration policy is blocking this path to safety.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek equal treatment or the right to choose to return to their homeland.
But in practice, they are trapped in a state of almost indefinite stagnation.
In theory, the refugee issue is a responsibility shared by all countries.
In reality, geographical location means that countries close to conflicts are overwhelmingly burdened with receiving the majority of refugees.
The provisions of the existing refugee system are not the cause of its collapse.
It is not that we have not adequately adapted to the changing world, but that is what we need to reconsider.
